0:{"rsc":["$","$1","c",{"children":[["$","div",null,{"className":"markdown-container","children":[["$","h1","h1-0",{"children":"History of Automation: Part 2"}],"\n",["$","h2","h2-0",{"children":"The Electronic & Control Age (1900 – 1990)"}],"\n",["$","p","p-0",{"children":[["$","strong","strong-0",{"children":"Scope"}],": The formalization of PID control, the birth of industrial robotics, PLCs, and Computer Numerical Control (CNC)."]}],"\n",["$","hr","hr-0",{}],"\n",["$","h2","h2-1",{"children":"1. Early 20th Century Innovations"}],"\n",["$","h3","h3-0",{"children":"1913: Henry Ford's Assembly Line"}],"\n",["$","p","p-1",{"children":[["$","strong","strong-0",{"children":"Event"}],": Ford implements a moving assembly line for Model T production.",["$","br","br-0",{}],"\n",["$","strong","strong-1",{"children":"Metrics"}],": Assembly time reduced from 728 hours per car to 93 hours (87.5% efficiency gain).",["$","br","br-1",{}],"\n",["$","strong","strong-2",{"children":"Significance"}],": Mechanized motion combined with task specialization creates exponential productivity gains, proving mass manufacturing profitability and catalyzing worldwide adoption."]}],"\n",["$","h3","h3-1",{"children":"1922: Nicolas Minorsky's PID Controller Theory"}],"\n",["$","p","p-2",{"children":[["$","strong","strong-0",{"children":"Event"}],": Minorsky publishes a mathematical analysis of ship steering control.",["$","br","br-0",{}],"\n",["$","strong","strong-1",{"children":"Key Insight"}],": Human helmsmen use three principles: Proportional (correct current error), Integral (accumulate past errors), and Derivative (anticipate future error).",["$","br","br-1",{}],"\n",["$","strong","strong-2",{"children":"Impact"}],": PID becomes the dominant control method for over 100 years. As of 2026, it still accounts for the vast majority of industrial controllers."]}],"\n",["$","h3","h3-2",{"children":"1943: Norbert Wiener's Cybernetics"}],"\n",["$","p","p-3",{"children":[["$","strong","strong-0",{"children":"Event"}],": Rosenblueth, Wiener, and Bigelow publish \"Behavior, Purpose and Teleology\".",["$","br","br-0",{}],"\n",["$","strong","strong-1",{"children":"Thesis"}],": Feedback-driven goal-seeking behavior is a universal principle applying to animals, machines, and organizations.",["$","br","br-1",{}],"\n",["$","strong","strong-2",{"children":"Impact"}],": Establishes automation and systems engineering as a rigorous scientific discipline."]}],"\n",["$","h3","h3-3",{"children":"1949: John T. Parsons & First CNC Machine"}],"\n",["$","p","p-4",{"children":[["$","strong","strong-0",{"children":"Event"}],": Working with MIT, Parsons develops a system to machine complex helicopter blade profiles by feeding coordinate data from punched cards into a servomotor-driven milling machine.\n",["$","strong","strong-1",{"children":"Significance"}],": The birth of Computer Numerical Control (CNC). This transitioned machining from human-guided tracing of physical templates to pure mathematical, digital precision, laying the groundwork for modern subtractive manufacturing."]}],"\n",["$","hr","hr-1",{}],"\n",["$","h2","h2-2",{"children":"2. Early Industrial Robotics (1950 - 1980)"}],"\n",["$","h3","h3-4",{"children":"1954: George Devol's Unimate Robot"}],"\n",["$","p","p-5",{"children":[["$","strong","strong-0",{"children":"Event"}],": George Devol designs the first programmable industrial robot arm, powered by hydraulics.",["$","br","br-0",{}],"\n",["$","strong","strong-1",{"children":"Technical Specs"}],": 6 degrees of freedom, punched tape memory, ±1 inch accuracy at a 5-foot reach.",["$","br","br-1",{}],"\n",["$","strong","strong-2",{"children":"Innovation"}],": Combines programmable memory (Jacquard loom principle) with electrical control and mechanical manipulation."]}],"\n",["$","h3","h3-5",{"children":"1961: First Industrial Robot Deployment (GM Plant)"}],"\n","$L2","\n","$L3","\n","$L4","\n","$L5","\n","$L6","\n","$L7","\n","$L8","\n","$L9","\n","$La","\n","$Lb","\n","$Lc"]}],null,"$Ld"]}],"isPartial":false,"staleTime":300,"varyParams":null,"buildId":"sFzo4LKMJghR7e79YRpfU"}
2:["$","p","p-6",{"children":[["$","strong","strong-0",{"children":"Event"}],": The Unimate robot is installed at the General Motors Ewing, New Jersey facility.",["$","br","br-0",{}],"\n",["$","strong","strong-1",{"children":"Application"}],": Casting part extraction and die-casting machine tending (a highly dangerous, repetitive task).",["$","br","br-1",{}],"\n",["$","strong","strong-2",{"children":"Impact"}],": Proves the commercial viability of industrial robots and marks the definitive birth of the robotics industry."]}]
3:["$","h3","h3-6",{"children":"1968: Dick Morley's Programmable Logic Controller (PLC)"}]
4:["$","p","p-7",{"children":[["$","strong","strong-0",{"children":"Event"}],": Dick Morley designs the first PLC for Bedford Associates.",["$","br","br-0",{}],"\n",["$","strong","strong-1",{"children":"Problem Solved"}],": Hard-wired relay logic circuits were inflexible and required complete rewiring for any process changes.",["$","br","br-1",{}],"\n",["$","strong","strong-2",{"children":"Solution"}],": Replace physical relays with solid-state switching; program the logic in software using \"ladder logic.\"",["$","br","br-2",{}],"\n",["$","strong","strong-3",{"children":"Impact"}],": Completely transforms industrial process control, enabling rapid reconfiguration of factory lines."]}]
5:["$","h3","h3-7",{"children":"1973: 6-Axis Industrial Robot Arm"}]
6:["$","p","p-8",{"children":[["$","strong","strong-0",{"children":"Event"}],": Development of the first electrically-driven, 6-DOF robot arm with servo feedback control.",["$","br","br-0",{}],"\n",["$","strong","strong-1",{"children":"Advancement"}],": Moves the industry beyond hydraulics, enabling much finer control and lower maintenance.",["$","br","br-1",{}],"\n",["$","strong","strong-2",{"children":"Impact"}],": Leads to widespread deployment of welding and assembly robots in automotive manufacturing by KUKA, ABB, and FANUC."]}]
7:["$","hr","hr-2",{}]
8:["$","h2","h2-3",{"children":"3. Digital Control & Early Networking (1980 - 1990)"}]
9:["$","h3","h3-8",{"children":"1983: SCADA Systems Emerge"}]
a:["$","p","p-9",{"children":[["$","strong","strong-0",{"children":"Event"}],": Supervisory Control and Data Acquisition (SCADA) systems become widespread for centralized monitoring.",["$","br","br-0",{}],"\n",["$","strong","strong-1",{"children":"Architecture"}],": Central control centers communicating via telecommunications to Remote Terminal Units (RTUs) at the edge.",["$","br","br-1",{}],"\n",["$","strong","strong-2",{"children":"Impact"}],": Enables the remote operation of geographically massive critical infrastructure (power grids, water treatment, pipelines)."]}]
b:["$","hr","hr-3",{}]
